WEBVTT

00:01.090 --> 00:03.390
Scrub in with The Resident.

00:03.420 --> 00:06.060
Everything you thought
you knew about medicine
is wrong.

00:06.090 --> 00:09.090
Catch all-new episodes Mondays,
and check out our other
Fox programs...

00:09.130 --> 00:11.860
9-1-1, Empire,
and Lethal Weapon.

00:11.900 --> 00:13.700
- A little help... here?
- Hey, Rog.

00:13.730 --> 00:15.770
Only on Fox.

00:17.330 --> 00:18.891
Previously on The Resident...

00:18.901 --> 00:19.933
I got a question for you.

00:19.943 --> 00:21.578
Old friend's developed
a bit of a tremor.

00:21.588 --> 00:23.130
What about benzodiazepines?

00:23.140 --> 00:24.933
DEVON: Dr. Hunter,
if there's ever an opportunity

00:24.942 --> 00:26.601
to help you with your research,
count me in.

00:26.610 --> 00:29.047
NIC: I saw Lily earlier.
She didn't look good.

00:29.058 --> 00:32.069
I went to check Lily's files,
and they were missing.

00:32.080 --> 00:33.992
CONRAD: Dr. Hunter keeps
her patients' records separate

00:34.001 --> 00:35.981
on her own server at her
clinics, not at the hospital.

00:35.990 --> 00:37.774
JUDE: The operation came off
without a hitch.

00:37.784 --> 00:39.448
You had a spectacular surgeon.

00:39.544 --> 00:41.874
- Cake.
- CLAIRE: Louisa will be taken care of.

00:41.885 --> 00:45.176
But I have to pull
$2 million out of thin air.

00:45.185 --> 00:47.120
Be prepared to be woefully understaffed

00:47.130 --> 00:49.910
for the next 12 months.

00:51.078 --> 00:53.355
[SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE]

00:56.000 --> 00:58.508
[CAMERA PHONE CLICKING]

01:04.010 --> 01:06.918
Hi. Patient in bed six
was triaged as acute.

01:06.928 --> 01:09.677
Uh, he said his pain was a ten.

01:09.687 --> 01:12.363
Ear pain is always rated
the lowest priority: basic.

01:12.373 --> 01:16.338
Certainly not acute, which means
"big deal emergency."

01:17.656 --> 01:19.029
When is Nurse Hundley back?

01:19.039 --> 01:20.462
Oh, she's at St. John's now.

01:20.472 --> 01:22.120
Budget cuts or something.

01:22.130 --> 01:23.476
I got your back.

01:28.849 --> 01:30.759
[ALARM SOUNDING, SIREN WAILING]

01:30.770 --> 01:32.769
Tachy, intra-abdominal bleeding,
possible liver lac,

01:32.780 --> 01:34.460
- and a right-sided pneumothorax.
- Acute?

01:34.472 --> 01:36.409
Bus overturned on I-85,
multi casualties.

01:36.420 --> 01:38.524
- Ambulances are stacking up outside.
- Page Dr. Hawkins.

01:38.535 --> 01:39.926
We need help down here.

01:39.936 --> 01:42.190
Bilateral femur fractures.
Hypotension, JVD,

01:42.202 --> 01:44.622
and muffled heart sounds
indicate cardiac tamponade.

01:44.858 --> 01:48.400
Both acute... uh, Trauma Bay Two
and, uh, bed eight.

01:51.756 --> 01:53.005
Where is everyone?

01:53.023 --> 01:55.411
It's all blowback from helping Louisa.
Our budget was cut.

01:55.422 --> 01:57.470
ER staff nearly halved
midnight-to-noon shift.

01:57.800 --> 01:59.637
Right, well, we have Claire
to thank for that.

01:59.648 --> 02:00.797
Nurse Hundley was let go.

02:00.807 --> 02:02.671
Too experienced, too good,
too expensive.

02:02.681 --> 02:04.545
And the new triage nurse
is a bubblehead.

02:05.847 --> 02:07.646
- All right, let's go.
- Urgent?

02:07.657 --> 02:11.045
I-I don't want to tell you how to do
your job, but she's awake and breathing.

02:11.251 --> 02:12.349
Uh... basic.

02:12.360 --> 02:14.380
- My hand hurts.
- Yes, ma'am.

02:14.550 --> 02:15.807
Hey.

02:15.818 --> 02:17.748
Hey, I need to see a doctor, I think.

02:17.759 --> 02:20.580
I wiped out on my skateboard,
I wasn't wearing my helmet.

02:20.703 --> 02:22.717
- Um... Yeah, um...
- My head hurts a little bit.

02:22.728 --> 02:25.049
- Little road rash.
- Okay, a headache, uh, road rash.

02:25.060 --> 02:27.518
Uh, still breathing. Basic.
Please, just, uh, take a seat

02:27.530 --> 02:29.448
in the waiting room.

02:31.004 --> 02:32.922
[SIREN WAILING]

02:38.616 --> 02:41.027
[WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

02:42.180 --> 02:43.500
DEVON: Charge.

02:43.518 --> 02:44.538
Clear.

02:44.549 --> 02:45.656
Shock.

02:46.626 --> 02:48.060
Still no pulse.

02:49.082 --> 02:50.760
Hair acts as an insulator,

02:50.770 --> 02:52.754
and prevents the shock
from getting to the heart,

02:52.764 --> 02:55.447
which is the point
of the defibrillation, so...

02:55.457 --> 02:59.235
we remove it. Then we reapply
directly to the skin.

03:02.070 --> 03:03.438
Charge.

03:03.447 --> 03:04.527
Clear.

03:04.735 --> 03:05.736
Shock.

03:07.200 --> 03:08.489
Sinus rhythm.

03:08.501 --> 03:10.652
[MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY]

03:14.710 --> 03:16.081
Where's your I.D. bracelet?

03:16.091 --> 03:17.833
Didn't get one.

03:17.842 --> 03:20.703
Think I could get an aspirin?
Head's killing me.

03:20.713 --> 03:23.074
Not until you see the doctor.
I'll get you an I.D., though.

03:29.160 --> 03:30.570
Hey.

03:30.830 --> 03:33.232
♪ ♪

03:35.060 --> 03:38.559
♪ Push your hand through ♪
♪ the door, pickin' every lock ♪

03:38.570 --> 03:39.698
♪ Make a quick escape... ♪

03:39.707 --> 03:42.195
[SIREN WAILING]

03:44.310 --> 03:46.093
MINA: Brent Carter?

03:46.110 --> 03:47.724
- It's okay.
- Yeah. [GROANS]

03:47.740 --> 03:48.741
Dislocated shoulder.

03:48.750 --> 03:49.927
I've got it.

03:50.351 --> 03:51.729
[YELLS]

03:51.740 --> 03:53.085
[GRUNTS]

03:53.150 --> 03:54.213
Good news is we fixed it.

03:54.580 --> 03:55.439
Better?

03:56.120 --> 03:57.158
BRENT: Yeah.

03:59.990 --> 04:01.343
NURSE: Here you go.

04:02.335 --> 04:05.839
- Excuse me, this isn't mine.
- [PHONE VIBRATES]

04:07.000 --> 04:13.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

04:19.459 --> 04:21.494
Hey, Irving, bed seven's

04:21.505 --> 04:23.730
in A-fib with RVR,
I'm giving ten of diltiazem.

04:23.997 --> 04:26.296
- Whatever, man. Just do it.
- WOMAN: Excuse me, Doctor.

04:26.307 --> 04:28.477
- Excuse me.
- Yes, we'll be right with you, ma'am.

04:28.489 --> 04:30.868
- Doctor, please.
- Oh.

04:32.490 --> 04:33.710
DEVON: Sir?

04:33.728 --> 04:35.745
Hey, sir.

04:35.896 --> 04:38.014
Let's get this guy to acute, now!

04:38.024 --> 04:39.520
Get his vitals, start an IV.

04:39.530 --> 04:41.343
Let's have the intubation cart
standing by.

04:42.549 --> 04:43.791
He's unresponsive. Pulse is weak.

04:43.802 --> 04:46.592
Double access, wide open fluids,
peripheral Neo for now.

04:46.602 --> 04:47.660
Dr. Okafor, tube him.

04:47.670 --> 04:48.805
MINA: On it.

04:51.416 --> 04:52.798
Damn it. Left pupil is blown.

04:52.809 --> 04:54.810
Looks like we have a brain
bleed. Do we have images?

04:54.821 --> 04:57.426
There's no I.D. bracelet, so
there's no way to know if there

04:57.436 --> 04:58.763
- are tests.
- Is he gonna be okay?

04:58.773 --> 05:00.276
Where is this patient's I.D. bracelet?

05:00.287 --> 05:02.543
- Has he even been checked in?
- I-I didn't have time.

05:02.553 --> 05:03.809
- Um...
- CONRAD: What's his name?

05:03.820 --> 05:05.553
Find his name.

05:10.820 --> 05:12.644
Uh, Ian. His name is Ian Robinson.

05:12.656 --> 05:14.878
- Ian, can you hear me?
- CONRAD: He can't hear you.

05:14.890 --> 05:16.686
My best guess is a subdural hematoma.

05:16.699 --> 05:18.283
The bleed must be compressing
his brain stem.

05:18.295 --> 05:20.667
Well, is there another way to
relieve the pressure? Burr holes?

05:20.679 --> 05:22.692
Not without scans to
know where the bleed is.

05:22.704 --> 05:24.498
I can't just blindly drill into a brain.

05:24.510 --> 05:27.766
But he's gonna be okay, right? Because
he-he said he just had a headache.

05:27.777 --> 05:29.810
[MONITOR BEEPING]

05:29.820 --> 05:31.515
[SUSTAINED BEEP]

05:39.022 --> 05:40.151
[PHONE CHIMES]

06:03.810 --> 06:05.038
TIFFANY: [SNIFFLES] Please.

06:05.050 --> 06:07.478
Please, no, he...

06:07.488 --> 06:09.575
He can't...

06:11.420 --> 06:13.256
CONRAD: He has no I.D. bracelet.

06:13.267 --> 06:15.331
You didn't even admit him properly.

06:15.538 --> 06:18.556
So we have to learn his name
in the middle of a code?

06:20.236 --> 06:21.282
Ian.

06:21.293 --> 06:22.729
His name is Ian.

06:22.860 --> 06:24.711
I found him.

06:24.722 --> 06:28.066
Just lying over there,
unattended, in basic.

06:28.077 --> 06:30.109
Why didn't you triage Ian properly?

06:30.782 --> 06:32.559
It's my first day.

06:33.680 --> 06:34.916
Oh, man.

06:34.928 --> 06:37.967
He had a head injury.
That's, at minimum, urgent.

06:37.980 --> 06:40.035
- Always.
- TIFFANY: We were so busy...

06:40.045 --> 06:42.200
and he-he seemed okay.

06:42.211 --> 06:45.142
With brain bleeds, there aren't
always symptoms at first.

06:45.153 --> 06:47.403
He had a head injury.

06:47.988 --> 06:51.097
He should be on concussion protocol...

06:51.107 --> 06:52.790
in urgent.

06:52.800 --> 06:55.670
TIFFANY: The patients,
they just... they kept coming.

06:55.680 --> 06:58.375
And I-I didn't want to him to be
marked as urgent if he was basic.

06:58.386 --> 07:01.257
It's better to be overly
cautious with a head injury.

07:01.268 --> 07:03.155
Now you know what happens
when you aren't.

07:03.166 --> 07:06.752
Next time your patient won't end up
like Ian, dying alone, in basic.

07:06.763 --> 07:08.936
All right, everyone,
let's get back to work.

07:08.947 --> 07:10.869
Someone is dead because of her mistake.

07:10.880 --> 07:15.044
Yeah, and she'll always
carry that with her.

07:18.320 --> 07:19.484
He's right.

07:19.495 --> 07:20.617
We need to move on,

07:20.628 --> 07:23.134
and focus on the patients
that we can help.

07:27.763 --> 07:29.723
Abdominal pain. Bed two.

07:30.995 --> 07:32.332
All you.

07:37.970 --> 07:39.399
NIC: Heart rate is 120.

07:39.417 --> 07:41.951
Blood pressure is 110/60.

07:42.380 --> 07:43.629
That's bad.

07:44.399 --> 07:47.586
Well, it just means your body is working
hard to fight off this infection.

07:47.596 --> 07:50.015
Okay, well, Dr. Hunter
just gave me mega antibiotics,

07:50.026 --> 07:51.871
so it should start working soon.

07:52.056 --> 07:54.266
I'm so sorry you're going
through this, Lily.

07:54.356 --> 07:56.235
Your immune system was not strong enough

07:56.246 --> 07:58.857
the last time you left the hospital.
We should've kept you longer.

07:58.868 --> 08:00.946
No, it's not Dr. Hunter's fault.

08:01.413 --> 08:04.219
I mean, she knows what she's doing.

08:04.230 --> 08:05.472
Of course.

08:05.483 --> 08:07.678
Dr. Hunter has a great reputation.

08:07.787 --> 08:11.248
Yeah. She's the best oncologist
in Georgia.

08:12.942 --> 08:15.384
Hey, how long have you had this rash?

08:15.924 --> 08:18.069
Um, just since this morning.

08:19.080 --> 08:20.543
It really itches.

08:20.723 --> 08:23.793
As I remember, you don't have any
allergies to any medications, right?

08:23.804 --> 08:25.704
Uh, honestly, I-I can't remember.

08:26.187 --> 08:28.300
Sorry. The chemo's trashed my memory.

08:28.311 --> 08:31.193
But, I-it should be in my chart, right?

08:31.203 --> 08:33.460
Well, Dr. Hunter likes to keep
your paperwork at her clinic,

08:33.470 --> 08:35.679
but, um, let me see what I can do

08:35.690 --> 08:37.359
to get the information sent
over here, okay?

08:37.730 --> 08:40.169
- Okay.
- All right, I'll be back.

08:47.478 --> 08:49.487
Ian's father Paul's here.

08:49.911 --> 08:52.167
We're gonna go talk to him.

08:53.268 --> 08:56.490
You need to learn how to do one of the
hardest things we have to do as doctors.

08:57.348 --> 08:59.333
Let's go.

09:04.990 --> 09:07.473
CONRAD: Mr. Robinson,
I'm Dr. Conrad Hawkins.

09:07.483 --> 09:10.665
Your son Ian suffered a fall,

09:10.675 --> 09:13.230
and it led to a subdural hematoma,

09:13.240 --> 09:16.020
[FADING]:
which is a massive brain bleed.

09:18.240 --> 09:21.282
[ECHOES]: This was not
a survivable injury.

09:23.580 --> 09:24.984
PAUL: Ian's dead?

09:25.410 --> 09:26.623
CONRAD: Yes.

09:38.295 --> 09:40.485
Are you ready?

09:41.315 --> 09:42.578
Yeah.

09:51.581 --> 09:54.330
That... That-that's not Ian.

09:58.115 --> 09:59.984
That's not my boy.

10:12.300 --> 10:15.170
How's your day going?

10:15.182 --> 10:18.259
- Could use a do-over.
- Yeah.

10:18.470 --> 10:20.293
We took his picture.

10:20.304 --> 10:22.727
We'll ask everyone who comes in
if they recognize him.

10:22.738 --> 10:25.084
I'll circle back later in the day.

10:25.095 --> 10:26.574
Let me know if you find anything.

10:26.585 --> 10:27.878
You bet.

10:33.769 --> 10:36.603
I dropped off the John Doe
report with risk management.

10:36.614 --> 10:38.770
- Now what?
- Go upstairs and see our patients.

10:38.781 --> 10:42.704
Triple-check that anyone
who was admitted from the ER

10:42.715 --> 10:44.242
was properly diagnosed and treated.

10:44.260 --> 10:46.247
Who knows what mistakes
are coming our way.

10:48.600 --> 10:50.586
I'm counting on you.

10:50.595 --> 10:52.079
What about you?

10:52.089 --> 10:53.241
I'm staying here.

10:53.419 --> 10:55.205
I'll take over triage.

11:01.680 --> 11:03.037
CONRAD: Great.

11:03.048 --> 11:04.934
Show it to all the patients and everyone

11:04.945 --> 11:07.143
in the waiting area...
ask if anyone knows who he is.

11:07.153 --> 11:10.080
One thing we know for sure is
he isn't Ian Robinson.

11:10.727 --> 11:12.648
Has the real Ian Robinson showed up yet?

11:12.659 --> 11:15.823
No. Mr. Robinson isn't even sure
that his son was on that bus.

11:15.834 --> 11:19.156
Right now, we have no idea
how that backpack even got here.

11:22.400 --> 11:24.629
NIC: Lily's rash
is really bothering her.

11:24.639 --> 11:26.340
It's probably a superficial phlebitis.

11:26.840 --> 11:30.263
Change her IV and give her 25
of diphenhydramine.

11:30.274 --> 11:33.088
Of course. Also, would it be possible

11:33.098 --> 11:35.524
to get her complete chart
sent over from your clinic?

11:35.534 --> 11:37.367
What's wrong with her record here?

11:37.377 --> 11:39.697
Well, we weren't able to find it when
she was admitted...

11:39.708 --> 11:42.634
it seems to have... completely
vanished from our system.

11:42.645 --> 11:44.116
Huh. That's odd.

11:44.126 --> 11:46.695
And since Lily's
multiresistant infection

11:46.706 --> 11:50.048
is so difficult to treat, I figured
you'd probably be more comfortable

11:50.059 --> 11:52.163
if we had her entire history here.

11:54.960 --> 11:57.307
Of course. You're right.

11:57.318 --> 11:59.791
I'll have the clinic send it right over.

12:00.208 --> 12:02.117
Great. Thank you.

12:03.654 --> 12:06.350
So, how long till Shirley
passes the gallstone?

12:06.361 --> 12:08.498
We're trying to get
out of town for vacation.

12:08.510 --> 12:10.757
Well, it really depends
on how many stones there are.

12:10.769 --> 12:13.433
Any decreased appetite or weight loss?

12:13.444 --> 12:14.824
Shirley hasn't been eating much.

12:14.835 --> 12:16.979
Have you lost any weight?

12:16.990 --> 12:18.943
Not much. A pound?

12:18.954 --> 12:20.636
More like 15.

12:20.647 --> 12:22.939
Your husband is very attentive.

12:22.950 --> 12:24.801
Howie worries.

12:24.966 --> 12:26.962
But he's not my husband.

12:27.917 --> 12:31.055
- He's my boyfriend.
- [LAUGHS]

12:32.042 --> 12:35.327
We met six months ago
at an aero-modeling convention.

12:35.351 --> 12:38.929
We were both building exact replicas
of the Wright brothers' plane.

12:38.940 --> 12:40.772
- [CHUCKLING]
- Yeah. For us, it was love

12:40.780 --> 12:44.470
- at first Wright Flyer.
- [LAUGHING, COUGHING]

12:44.480 --> 12:45.701
- DEVON: Okay.
- Please, Doctor, please help her.

12:45.710 --> 12:47.292
- Oh, no, my...
- Okay.

12:47.303 --> 12:49.746
I'll increase your pain
med dose and frequency.

12:49.758 --> 12:50.883
Okay.

12:50.895 --> 12:53.448
As long as you're here,
we'll run a few more tests.

12:53.460 --> 12:55.593
- [BREATHLESS]: Thank you.
- I don't want Howie to worry.

12:55.604 --> 12:58.481
Then you better get
these gallstones out quick,

12:58.490 --> 13:01.239
so we can go on our trip and relax.

13:01.248 --> 13:03.576
[GROANS SOFTLY, SNIFFLES]

13:04.000 --> 13:06.741
- Deep breath.
- [INHALES]

13:08.066 --> 13:10.105
Oh, hey, Dr. Pravesh, I, uh...

13:12.263 --> 13:14.229
I want to touch base with you.

13:14.468 --> 13:16.383
I hope I didn't alarm you
by ordering more tests.

13:17.110 --> 13:19.554
It's probably just gallstones.

13:20.050 --> 13:21.389
Good.

13:21.401 --> 13:25.241
See, we're on our way
to Kitty Hawk and, uh...

13:25.252 --> 13:29.749
I'm gonna propose, in a big
romantic plane-themed gesture.

13:29.760 --> 13:31.820
- That's great.
- See, when you get to 80

13:31.830 --> 13:34.917
without a wife, you figure
nobody could ever love you.

13:35.720 --> 13:37.655
Then along comes my Shirley.

13:38.576 --> 13:41.466
She... she's my everything.

13:41.476 --> 13:43.857
And if I should propose early,

13:44.505 --> 13:46.464
you let me know.

13:46.475 --> 13:50.381
I'm a practical man, and I don't
want to be morbid, but...

13:51.710 --> 13:54.703
[CHUCKLES]: we're old.

13:54.713 --> 13:56.846
So please take good care of her.

14:02.720 --> 14:04.168
Things seem less chaotic.

14:04.179 --> 14:05.963
Made our way through the worst of it.

14:05.974 --> 14:08.799
Any word on the identity
of the John Doe we lost this morning?

14:08.810 --> 14:11.720
- Not yet.
- This is a new patient of ours.

14:11.730 --> 14:12.911
- Shirley Harris.
- [TYPING]

14:12.921 --> 14:15.601
Take a look at the ultrasound.

14:16.113 --> 14:18.767
The ER doc diagnosed gallstones.

14:19.416 --> 14:21.736
I'm afraid he missed a mass.

14:21.747 --> 14:23.165
What does the blood work show?

14:23.661 --> 14:25.816
Slight anemia. Weight loss.

14:25.826 --> 14:28.098
Let's get an EUS
to better characterize the mass

14:28.108 --> 14:30.376
and a CT for the surrounding areas.

14:30.388 --> 14:31.739
And we'll hope for the best.

14:31.750 --> 14:34.102
- Yeah. Let's hope.
- [TAPS KEY]

14:34.112 --> 14:35.851
[MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY]

14:40.160 --> 14:41.321
Kelly.

14:43.430 --> 14:46.874
- What are you doing?
- Preparing for the dissection.

14:46.886 --> 14:49.132
You aren't doing the dissection;
you're a resident.

14:49.144 --> 14:51.284
I do it for Dr. Bell.

14:51.295 --> 14:53.048
Well, he's not here.

14:53.060 --> 14:56.871
When I was a resident, they wouldn't
let me tie a knot unsupervised.

14:57.893 --> 14:59.125
Give me the Kelly.

15:00.650 --> 15:02.638
KAYS: Watch and learn.

15:02.650 --> 15:03.756
MINA: I have nothing to learn.

15:04.620 --> 15:07.804
KAYS: You are barely halfway
through training...

15:07.820 --> 15:09.773
there is plenty for you to learn.

15:09.783 --> 15:11.373
[SIGHS]

15:19.670 --> 15:22.206
Any action on this? How much you
gonna give me -if I make the putt?

15:22.216 --> 15:25.567
Huh. You haven't mentioned money
since you got a case of the yips.

15:25.577 --> 15:26.765
How much?

15:27.980 --> 15:29.750
- Hundred.
- You sure?

15:29.760 --> 15:31.711
Downhill, very slippery.

15:32.745 --> 15:35.145
- How about five?
- Easy money.

15:35.156 --> 15:37.359
You haven't even two-putted
in six months.

15:37.370 --> 15:38.593
Thousand?

15:39.654 --> 15:41.210
Fine.

15:41.221 --> 15:45.633
You miss, you donate a thousand bucks
to my son's school fund-raiser.

15:46.042 --> 15:48.213
Wonderful. For the kids.

15:48.224 --> 15:50.865
I miss the putt, thousand bucks
to your son's school.

15:50.876 --> 15:54.322
I sink it, thousand bucks to...

15:55.870 --> 15:57.900
me.

15:57.924 --> 16:00.402
[LAUGHS]

16:01.810 --> 16:04.465
♪ ♪

16:11.779 --> 16:13.711
Damn it! Man!

16:13.720 --> 16:15.633
[QUIETLY]: I'm back.

16:17.565 --> 16:18.656
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

16:21.648 --> 16:24.100
She made me hold the retractors
the entire time.

16:24.111 --> 16:26.842
- Like I was... an intern.
- Insanity.

16:26.854 --> 16:28.283
20-something male, John Doe,

16:28.294 --> 16:30.366
fractured left femur,
bruising to the right chest,

16:30.377 --> 16:32.924
- neck injury with possible crushed larynx.
- John Doe?

16:32.934 --> 16:35.383
I thought we had all the
casualties from the bus accident.

16:35.394 --> 16:37.497
He's the last one... found him
way off in some shrubs.

16:37.508 --> 16:38.768
He must have been thrown on impact.

16:38.779 --> 16:40.463
Okay, this could be our guy,
Ian Robinson.

16:40.474 --> 16:41.517
Take him to Trauma Two.

16:41.528 --> 16:44.409
Let's hope it's him... it'd be nice to
tell Paul we found his son, alive.

16:44.421 --> 16:45.523
Barely.

16:48.090 --> 16:49.482
- [COUGHS]
- He's desatting.

16:49.491 --> 16:51.564
Attending, get a GlideScope.

16:51.930 --> 16:53.537
CONRAD/MINA: Airway.

16:54.318 --> 16:56.932
Oh, no. No, no, that's surgery.
You can't do that in the ER.

16:56.943 --> 16:58.309
Not without attending supervision.

16:58.320 --> 17:01.940
By the time someone gets here, he'll
be brain-dead. Get the trach kit.

17:01.951 --> 17:04.898
- Are you sure?
- There's no choice.

17:04.910 --> 17:07.268
There is a choice... you could
choose to follow protocol.

17:07.279 --> 17:09.712
- The patient would die.
- I'm not telling that father

17:09.723 --> 17:11.875
his son is dead for a second time today.

17:14.268 --> 17:16.162
Don't do this.

17:17.387 --> 17:18.449
Stop!

17:20.619 --> 17:22.654
That's normal.

17:22.669 --> 17:24.980
- [SIGHS]
- [MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY]

17:29.170 --> 17:31.404
I'll take this photo up to Paul
Robinson and confirm he's his son.

17:33.170 --> 17:35.986
Not to point out
the obvious here, but you...

17:36.640 --> 17:38.632
are a badass.

17:40.561 --> 17:42.757
Let me see this badass's work.

17:44.335 --> 17:46.523
Surgery performed in the ER

17:46.918 --> 17:50.635
by an arrogant, overconfident,
unsupervised resident.

17:55.675 --> 17:57.727
Flawless technique.

17:57.737 --> 17:59.340
Mm, you know how to cut.

17:59.351 --> 18:01.501
But you don't know when not to.

18:01.512 --> 18:03.505
I'm benching you for the day. Clear?

18:04.830 --> 18:06.319
Get him up to my OR.

18:07.793 --> 18:10.055
That's unfair...
you saved the patient's life.

18:10.066 --> 18:11.483
Why didn't you say something?

18:11.494 --> 18:13.131
I want to cut tomorrow.

18:19.413 --> 18:20.497
Thank you.

18:20.508 --> 18:22.528
Yeah, we'll work on both of those.

18:22.539 --> 18:25.008
My office sent over
Lily's file... did you get it?

18:25.019 --> 18:26.240
Not yet.

18:27.814 --> 18:29.149
Are you sure? Did you check?

18:29.160 --> 18:31.520
- Did they e-mail it?
- We don't e-mail

18:31.530 --> 18:33.353
patient files; they're not secure.

18:33.363 --> 18:35.227
Well, let me check the fax.

18:37.382 --> 18:38.682
No fax.

18:38.870 --> 18:40.982
Is the paper tray empty?

18:40.991 --> 18:42.242
[SCOFFS SOFTLY]

18:43.010 --> 18:46.132
Nope, it's full, just waitin' for a fax.

18:46.142 --> 18:49.034
Well, my office sent it over.
The problem is on your end.

18:49.044 --> 18:51.313
It's a miracle people make it
out of this place alive.

18:51.324 --> 18:54.154
There's one person I wish wouldn't.

18:56.402 --> 18:58.568
Yes, that's my son.

18:58.578 --> 19:00.710
Thank you, Dr. Hawkins.

19:00.720 --> 19:03.750
He's in surgery; you can see him
just as soon as he's out.

19:03.760 --> 19:06.415
- Okay.
- We need his medical history.

19:06.436 --> 19:09.940
Is he allergic to anything?
Medications, food allergies?

19:09.953 --> 19:13.180
Any health conditions I should know
about? Heart condition, diabetes?

19:13.200 --> 19:17.579
Let's see, his doctor said
that he has low calcium.

19:24.669 --> 19:25.935
[MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY]

19:25.950 --> 19:28.914
Too much tension on my
carotid repair. Hold him still.

19:29.048 --> 19:31.019
- Hold him still.
- CONRAD: Baseline is hypocalcemic!

19:31.029 --> 19:33.238
The blood transfusion made it
worse... he needs calcium!

19:33.248 --> 19:35.511
Okay, well, add calcium to his IV.

19:35.520 --> 19:39.445
CHU: What IV? It tore right out
of his arm. We don't have access.

19:42.067 --> 19:44.317
I'll put in a new IV. Hold his arm.

19:44.329 --> 19:46.889
- I'll rip his arm out of the socket.
- The seizure won't stop

19:46.900 --> 19:49.575
until we get calcium into his veins.

19:52.576 --> 19:53.707
[GRUNTS]

19:55.940 --> 19:57.834
Don't let go, no matter what.

19:57.844 --> 20:00.624
KAYS: I need access now.
There's too much tension...

20:00.634 --> 20:02.594
Almost there. Almost there.

20:02.603 --> 20:05.588
- We're about to have a blowout
on our hands. - I'm in.

20:07.560 --> 20:09.376
Pushing calcium now.

20:15.015 --> 20:16.710
[MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY]

20:19.970 --> 20:22.640
Thank you.

20:25.327 --> 20:28.249
[EXHALES DEEPLY]

20:32.745 --> 20:36.221
[HEAVY BREATHING]

20:37.090 --> 20:40.630
NIC: It's gonna help with
your breathing, Lily, okay?

20:40.639 --> 20:43.206
- Page Dr. Hawkins.
- I already paged him.

20:43.215 --> 20:45.619
- Give me the epi.
- Nurses can't administer meds

20:45.628 --> 20:47.279
without orders.

20:50.190 --> 20:53.201
- [MUFFLED GROAN]
- Looks like they can.

20:55.610 --> 20:57.841
- Where have you been?
- In a stuffy room

20:57.850 --> 21:00.929
with stuffier administrators trying
to get them to rehire Nurse Hundley.

21:00.938 --> 21:03.576
Once I pointed out they could be
looking at a lawsuit, they caved.

21:03.585 --> 21:06.309
She'll be back in the ER
within the hour. She's wheezing.

21:06.318 --> 21:07.894
- What's hanging?
- Saline and imipenem.

21:07.904 --> 21:09.635
I just gave her epi.

21:10.346 --> 21:14.014
Stop the imipenem. Open the saline wide.
Lily, you're gonna be all right.

21:14.024 --> 21:15.880
I'm gonna sedate you
and put in a breathing tube

21:15.890 --> 21:18.322
- to keep your airway open.
- What's happening? [WHEEZES]

21:18.330 --> 21:21.320
[QUIETLY]: I'm here, Lily,
and I'm gonna take care of this.

21:21.330 --> 21:23.320
[WEAK, GASPING BREATHS]

21:23.330 --> 21:26.438
I have to figure out which one of
her meds is causing the reaction.

21:26.449 --> 21:28.106
There's... there's so many.

21:28.117 --> 21:29.764
Well, I don't remember her
having any sensitivity,

21:29.781 --> 21:31.728
so whatever it is, it's
got to be something new.

21:31.739 --> 21:34.854
Her only new med is the imipenem...
if it is that, we're screwed.

21:35.393 --> 21:37.499
Is she allergic
to any other antibiotics?

21:37.509 --> 21:39.008
Whoa, whoa, wait, wait, wait, hold on.

21:39.019 --> 21:41.564
Her chart only goes back as
far as this current admission.

21:41.574 --> 21:43.715
I know, and I've been trying
to get it sent over

21:43.725 --> 21:45.596
from Dr. Hunter's clinic
since this morning.

21:45.606 --> 21:47.803
They keep insisting they
sent it, but it never arrived.

21:47.814 --> 21:50.401
With Lily's infection,
I don't want to keep her off

21:50.411 --> 21:52.820
the broad-spectrum antibiotic
for long. We need her chart.

21:52.830 --> 21:56.418
Hey, Debbie, can you cover for
me for an hour? Can you stay?

21:56.428 --> 21:58.589
- Where you going?
- Lane's clinic.

21:58.599 --> 22:00.481
We obviously can't trust them

22:00.491 --> 22:02.900
to get us her chart,
so I'm gonna go get it myself.

22:02.910 --> 22:04.510
LANE: Just enhance that a bit more.

22:06.146 --> 22:09.370
- What have you found?
- Shirley Harris's EUS,

22:09.380 --> 22:12.620
CT and supporting lab work
confirm gallbladder cancer.

22:12.631 --> 22:16.532
But the good news is it's early stage
and confined in the gallbladder.

22:16.542 --> 22:19.299
So there is a real chance the
treatment could be curative for her?

22:19.310 --> 22:21.540
Well, we can certainly reduce
the chance of recurrence.

22:21.551 --> 22:23.623
The tumour’s located in the
neck of the gallbladder.

22:23.634 --> 22:26.605
In order to get clean margins, some
of her liver will have to be removed.

22:26.615 --> 22:28.866
- It is tricky.
- Tricky?

22:28.876 --> 22:32.930
It's a minefield of blood vessels
and bile ducts, and she's anemic.

22:32.940 --> 22:34.931
Clip the wrong vessel,
once the bleeding starts,

22:34.940 --> 22:36.828
we might not be able to stop it.

22:36.839 --> 22:38.796
At her advanced age,
there's a real chance

22:38.806 --> 22:40.831
she won't make it
through surgery... why risk it?

22:40.841 --> 22:42.748
I highly recommend a palliative consult.

22:42.758 --> 22:44.660
Shirley's 80 is a young 80.

22:44.670 --> 22:47.986
More like 60, full of life.
Her boyfriend's about to propose to her.

22:47.997 --> 22:52.022
- She has a lot to live for.
- If she makes it off the table.

22:52.033 --> 22:56.066
It has been done successfully before.

22:57.390 --> 22:58.696
Cancer?

22:59.532 --> 23:01.436
Gallbladder cancer?

23:01.446 --> 23:04.198
Yes. But because we caught it early,

23:04.208 --> 23:06.971
there's a real chance for a total cure.

23:06.981 --> 23:09.111
With surgery and radiation.

23:09.121 --> 23:12.193
That sounds simple,
but I'm guessing maybe it isn't.

23:12.203 --> 23:14.730
The surgery itself is-is complicated.

23:14.740 --> 23:16.236
HOWIE: How complicated?

23:16.246 --> 23:18.665
Could the surgery kill Shirley?

23:18.675 --> 23:21.678
This is a highly aggressive cancer.

23:21.687 --> 23:24.546
Without the surgery,
you could have less than a year.

23:24.556 --> 23:28.642
But with the surgery,
you can have many more years.

23:28.652 --> 23:30.446
HOWIE: Are you okay?

23:30.456 --> 23:31.928
Shirley, say something.

23:31.937 --> 23:33.638
I might be dying.

23:34.659 --> 23:38.393
And there's only one thing
I want to know.

23:38.970 --> 23:40.741
Howie Green...

23:41.950 --> 23:43.660
will you marry me?

23:43.667 --> 23:46.464
You're not supposed to ask me that,
Shirley Harris. I'm going to ask you.

23:46.471 --> 23:48.197
Don't be difficult.

23:48.205 --> 23:50.304
- Answer me.
- Yes.

23:50.312 --> 23:52.560
I will marry you,

23:52.567 --> 23:54.643
- only if you marry me.
- Yes!

23:54.650 --> 23:57.443
I will marry you. [LAUGHS]

24:04.194 --> 24:10.433
So, how do we make sure this
lifesaving surgery doesn't kill me?

24:10.446 --> 24:13.308
- 'Cause I got a wedding to go to.
- Yeah.

24:13.321 --> 24:15.798
In the hands of a lesser surgeon,

24:15.811 --> 24:19.088
I wouldn't be as confident,
but you're getting the best.

24:19.101 --> 24:22.567
Dr. Randolph Bell has
the highest success rate.

24:22.580 --> 24:23.673
SHIRLEY: The man on the billboards?

24:23.680 --> 24:25.691
LANE: Yes. He's our chief of surgery.

24:25.703 --> 24:28.508
CONRAD: Are you sure Dr.
Bell is right for this case?

24:28.520 --> 24:31.308
He's done hepatobiliary
surgeries many times.

24:31.317 --> 24:34.691
There's no one else here
who can touch his record.

24:34.701 --> 24:37.457
It's his record I'm worried about.

24:37.466 --> 24:39.566
His complication rates have
risen dramatically lately.

24:39.576 --> 24:41.142
And I only bring this up because I know

24:41.153 --> 24:43.110
attendings aren't always
aware of their colleagues.

24:43.121 --> 24:47.090
- Every doctor makes mistakes.
- Of course, but this is far beyond.

24:47.100 --> 24:49.996
Conrad, hold on.

24:50.006 --> 24:53.108
I'm gonna speak to you now
as a dear friend and mentor.

24:53.118 --> 24:55.958
You're one of the most gifted
young residents I know.

24:55.968 --> 24:58.841
Don't sabotage a career
that's just beginning.

24:58.851 --> 25:02.430
Doctors must support each other
through good times and bad.

25:02.440 --> 25:04.584
You, of all people, should know that.

25:04.594 --> 25:06.598
I'm grateful for all
you did for me in the past,

25:06.608 --> 25:09.865
- but I have to speak for my patient.
- Shirley's my patient now.

25:09.875 --> 25:13.136
She wants Bell, who's my choice.

25:14.396 --> 25:17.271
Let's all get on the same page
with this decision.

25:17.281 --> 25:18.561
Shall we?

25:19.970 --> 25:21.153
Excellent.

25:33.050 --> 25:37.081
♪ Money, money ♪
♪ I just can't get enough ♪

25:37.090 --> 25:38.915
♪ Dollar, dollar I just
can't give it up ♪

25:38.920 --> 25:42.380
♪ Brother, brother, I'm ♪
♪ working overtime... ♪

25:42.390 --> 25:44.923
What would it take to get you unbenched?

25:47.336 --> 25:48.939
[SIGHS]

25:48.949 --> 25:50.926
[DOOR OPENS]

25:52.330 --> 25:56.190
The inflammation makes it hard to
get a good view of the anatomy.

25:56.200 --> 26:00.059
If I were assisting, I could clear
the field for you to do that.

26:00.069 --> 26:02.302
Dr. KAYS benched you.

26:02.312 --> 26:05.305
You're the chief of surgery.
You can unbench me.

26:05.315 --> 26:06.934
I could.

26:09.495 --> 26:11.933
It's a difficult surgery.

26:13.305 --> 26:16.958
What exactly are you implying?

26:16.968 --> 26:21.824
I'm saying your success rate
is better when I'm beside you.

26:21.834 --> 26:24.243
I agree with Dr. KAYS' assessment.

26:24.253 --> 26:27.066
You have gotten
a little full of yourself.

26:28.672 --> 26:31.195
Take the day off.

26:44.850 --> 26:47.945
- Hi.
- Hi.

26:47.955 --> 26:50.680
- How can I make your day better?
- I'm NIC Nevin, from Chastain.

26:50.690 --> 26:53.022
We're still waiting
on Lily Kendall's records.

26:53.032 --> 26:55.031
Yeah, I faxed everything.

26:55.041 --> 26:58.740
Right, um, and I'm sure
the problem's on our end,

26:58.750 --> 27:01.331
but since I'm here, if you wouldn't
mind just making me a copy...

27:01.341 --> 27:04.312
- Wait in the lobby.
- Sure.

27:17.930 --> 27:21.461
Nurse Hundley. You're back!

27:21.471 --> 27:25.250
- You're back! Oh...
- [LAUGHS]

27:25.260 --> 27:28.890
As much as I love to see
a man on his knees,

27:28.900 --> 27:30.909
get up, Dr. Feldman.

27:30.919 --> 27:33.702
This place is a mess.

27:41.443 --> 27:42.777
Allie?

27:44.350 --> 27:46.646
- NIC?
- [CHUCKLES]

27:46.656 --> 27:50.779
- I haven't seen you since...
- Nursing school.

27:52.549 --> 27:55.219
- Wait, you're not here for...
- Oh, no, no, not a patient.

27:55.229 --> 27:57.073
No, I'm just waiting on some records.

27:57.083 --> 28:00.014
Good. I have to get back to work.

28:00.024 --> 28:02.927
- We should catch up soon.
- I would love that.

28:02.937 --> 28:04.844
- All right, I'll see you.
- Okay.

28:34.400 --> 28:36.143
MAN: Can I help you?

28:36.153 --> 28:39.058
Oh, I was just, uh,
admiring the facility.

28:39.279 --> 28:41.349
That treatment room is incredible.

28:41.359 --> 28:43.437
You can treat so many patients
at the same time.

28:43.447 --> 28:45.264
Dr. Hunter doesn't want
to turn patients away,

28:45.274 --> 28:47.845
so we squeeze in as many as possible.

28:49.447 --> 28:52.118
- Here's the file.
- All right,

28:52.128 --> 28:54.963
- let me just make sure it's all here.
- It is.

28:57.450 --> 29:00.623
Okay. Well, thank you.

29:00.633 --> 29:02.363
Bye-bye.

29:09.190 --> 29:11.364
Excuse me, Dr. Hunter.

29:11.375 --> 29:13.428
LANE: Dr. Pravesh.

29:14.298 --> 29:17.213
I wrote a paper on intraoperative
radiation therapy,

29:17.223 --> 29:20.229
so I would love
to observe this afternoon.

29:20.240 --> 29:24.259
Well, you're certainly welcome to
observe, if there is a procedure.

29:24.269 --> 29:26.083
Medicare hasn't signed off yet.

29:26.093 --> 29:27.670
Let me take that off your plate.

29:27.680 --> 29:30.970
That's industrious.
I like that. Be warned,

29:30.980 --> 29:34.610
Medicare doesn't like to approve
expensive experimental procedures.

29:34.620 --> 29:37.783
Oh, no worries.
I can be very persuasive.

29:40.545 --> 29:43.236
- Please. Please don't hang up.
- [LINE CLICKS]

29:44.300 --> 29:46.164
They hung up. Unbelievable.

29:46.174 --> 29:48.524
Or believable.

29:48.534 --> 29:52.000
DEVON: I'm a physician calling
on behalf of Shirley Harris.

29:52.010 --> 29:54.502
Shirley Harris. H-A-R-R...

29:54.512 --> 29:57.087
I cannot hold again, okay?
Don't you dare... [GROANS]

29:57.097 --> 30:00.694
Hi, yes. I need approval
on an experimental...

30:00.704 --> 30:03.476
Yes, I'll hold. No, I will not hold!

30:03.486 --> 30:05.311
I have been hung up on seven times

30:05.320 --> 30:07.379
and on hold for over an hour
and 20 minutes!

30:07.389 --> 30:10.115
There's no code
because it is a new procedure.

30:10.125 --> 30:15.202
Without the tumour resection and
the adjunct radiation procedure,

30:15.212 --> 30:17.604
the patient will die.

30:18.370 --> 30:20.179
Can you hold on a minute?

30:22.630 --> 30:24.914
You will?

30:25.446 --> 30:28.557
Oh, that's awesome. Oh, I'm so relieved.

30:28.567 --> 30:30.342
Thank you.

30:34.369 --> 30:37.078
Whoa, whoa. Uh, where are you going?

30:37.089 --> 30:38.680
Kitty Hawk.

30:38.690 --> 30:41.941
You have surgery this afternoon.
I just got it authorized.

30:41.951 --> 30:45.434
- It took four hours.
- SHIRLEY: Sorry.

30:45.444 --> 30:47.358
Can't make it.

30:47.369 --> 30:49.999
I'll be standing
at the birthplace of aviation,

30:50.009 --> 30:52.401
marrying the love of my life.

30:52.412 --> 30:55.790
After our honeymoon, we'll come
back and fight the cancer together.

30:55.800 --> 30:58.559
Right now there is a window of time

30:58.570 --> 31:01.038
where the cancer is contained
and we can remove it all.

31:01.048 --> 31:03.722
If we wait, the disease will spread.

31:03.732 --> 31:05.477
Dr. Pravesh...

31:05.487 --> 31:07.679
you don't know
that the cancer will spread

31:07.689 --> 31:09.796
or if the surgery will kill me,

31:09.806 --> 31:13.650
but I know that when I die,

31:13.660 --> 31:16.265
I will be this man's wife.

31:16.936 --> 31:18.977
We're going to Kitty Hawk.

31:18.987 --> 31:24.083
Wait. Please. What if you could get
married and have the surgery today?

31:24.093 --> 31:26.199
We want to be married at Kitty Hawk.

31:26.209 --> 31:28.642
Then I'll bring Kitty Hawk to you.

31:32.010 --> 31:33.901
CONRAD: How'd you score
the model airplanes?

31:33.910 --> 31:36.157
DEVON: Howie has hundreds of them.

31:38.734 --> 31:41.171
[CAMERA CLICKS]

31:41.180 --> 31:43.380
♪ ♪

31:43.391 --> 31:46.489
So, Irving is a licensed minister?

31:46.500 --> 31:50.419
And willing to write a wedding
ceremony filled with airplane puns.

31:50.430 --> 31:52.433
Less surprising.

31:53.060 --> 31:55.148
- [CAMERA CLICKS]
- The photographer?

31:55.158 --> 31:58.518
Publicist. Renata loves a PR moment.

32:00.140 --> 32:03.256
DEVON: A hospital story
with a happy ending.

32:05.470 --> 32:08.646
As long as Bell doesn't kill her
on the OR table.

32:12.235 --> 32:15.021
[MONITOR BEEPING]

32:45.850 --> 32:48.284
CONRAD: Okay, thank you.

32:48.293 --> 32:51.627
Right, let me know
if anything does turn up.

32:51.636 --> 32:55.250
Still trying to identify the poor
guy we lost in the ER this morning?

32:55.260 --> 32:57.519
CONRAD: Police are checking
missing persons reports.

32:57.529 --> 33:00.544
I don't know what else to
do to find out who he is.

33:00.554 --> 33:04.192
You understand we can only save
the living ones.

33:04.202 --> 33:05.460
- Right?
- Yeah.

33:05.470 --> 33:07.978
But I can't get his family
out of my head.

33:10.828 --> 33:13.251
What is this thing?

33:13.261 --> 33:16.378
Some sort of lifesaving
playing-card-ectomy?

33:24.953 --> 33:26.784
You should go now.

33:29.190 --> 33:31.279
Mm-hmm.

33:41.961 --> 33:44.049
I'll take it from here, Howie.

33:44.059 --> 33:46.446
To cross this line,
you have to be sterile.

33:49.336 --> 33:53.076
I'm so happy you're my wife, Mrs. Green.

33:53.086 --> 33:55.466
Well, get used to it.

33:55.476 --> 33:58.958
I'll see you when I wake up, Mr. Green.

34:02.312 --> 34:04.580
She's in good hands.

34:04.590 --> 34:06.396
Thank you.

34:18.393 --> 34:20.322
[MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY]

34:30.590 --> 34:32.559
♪ ♪

34:46.495 --> 34:51.472
- Beautiful incision, Dr. Bell.
- Thank you, Jessica. Suction.

34:54.648 --> 34:57.251
Okay. All set.

34:57.261 --> 34:58.748
So we use the Mobetron

34:58.758 --> 35:01.893
because it allows the electrons
to precisely deliver radiation

35:01.903 --> 35:05.135
and limit the spread to
non-affected organs.

35:05.145 --> 35:08.047
Exactly. We'll give one
large fraction dosage.

35:08.057 --> 35:10.050
Well, don't you need
a radiation oncologist?

35:10.060 --> 35:11.458
I'm double-boarded.

35:11.468 --> 35:13.820
[MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY]

35:13.830 --> 35:16.790
Blood pressure's dropping, Dr. Bell.

35:16.800 --> 35:19.143
It's fine as a bleeder.
It's nothing I can't handle.

35:24.717 --> 35:26.856
[RAPID BEEPING CONTINUES]

35:30.595 --> 35:34.104
- Do you need assistance?
- No, I need quiet so I can work.

35:42.453 --> 35:44.224
Vascular clamp.

35:46.830 --> 35:48.212
307.

35:58.458 --> 36:00.145
Run fluids. Wide open.

36:03.471 --> 36:06.870
- [BEEPING SLOWS]
- We're good.

36:06.880 --> 36:10.339
Change the music, something upbeat.

36:10.350 --> 36:12.781
♪ Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa ♪

36:12.790 --> 36:14.318
All right, we're on.

36:14.328 --> 36:17.601
So, it was a question of anatomy

36:17.611 --> 36:19.715
'cause hers was atypical.

36:19.725 --> 36:21.422
Though it didn't show up on imaging,

36:21.432 --> 36:24.753
the common hepatic artery
was not in its normal position.

36:24.763 --> 36:28.012
And a less-experienced surgeon
wouldn't have known to look for that.

36:28.022 --> 36:31.268
They would have tied it off
like a bleeder, not realizing

36:31.278 --> 36:33.670
they're cutting off the entire
blood supply to the liver.

36:33.680 --> 36:35.533
Because I've seen it before,

36:35.543 --> 36:39.554
now I routinely look for it,
and that habitual extra precaution,

36:39.565 --> 36:41.897
well, that just helped me avoid
a deadly complication.

36:41.907 --> 36:44.880
And now, I believe
she has a honeymoon to go on.

36:44.890 --> 36:47.782
Well, I'm certainly happy
we had you today, Dr. Bell.

36:47.790 --> 36:52.316
♪ Everything I touch ♪

36:52.330 --> 36:55.752
♪ Burns right down To dust ♪
♪ 'cause I'm reckless ♪

36:55.760 --> 36:58.527
♪ Yeah, I'm reckless ♪

36:59.630 --> 37:01.294
♪ And I always seem to fall ♪

37:01.300 --> 37:04.558
♪ On the wrong side of the law ♪

37:04.570 --> 37:06.799
♪ 'Cause I'm reckless ♪

37:06.810 --> 37:08.900
♪ And I can't help ♪

37:08.910 --> 37:11.136
♪ My reckless ways. ♪

37:11.146 --> 37:12.956
I hear you went to my clinic.

37:14.483 --> 37:15.766
I did.

37:15.776 --> 37:20.652
I did. I was impressed. Beautiful
architecture. Inspiring, really.

37:20.662 --> 37:23.366
Mm. You're very dedicated.

37:24.490 --> 37:26.388
A real gem.

37:41.126 --> 37:43.058
[SIGHS]

37:45.780 --> 37:50.104
Tumour margins clean.
Clear nodes. [CHUCKLES]

37:50.113 --> 37:52.354
With my hands and your radiation,

37:52.364 --> 37:55.167
we didn't just buy her
more time, we cured her.

37:56.726 --> 37:59.214
You know, I've been married twice.

37:59.223 --> 38:02.062
Had my share of affairs,
but I've never really...

38:02.071 --> 38:05.899
had love like that. But that
right there is why I do this.

38:05.900 --> 38:07.039
LANE: Really?

38:07.050 --> 38:09.655
Would you have done the surgery
if Medicare had refused to pay?

38:09.665 --> 38:14.426
No, of course not.
I'm not some gung ho resident.

38:14.436 --> 38:16.308
Would you?

38:16.318 --> 38:19.269
Top Ramen got me through my residency.

38:19.280 --> 38:22.494
I'm serious. It took me years
to pay off my student loans.

38:22.504 --> 38:24.310
Yeah.

38:24.320 --> 38:25.741
Now...

38:25.750 --> 38:27.914
we're the best at what we do.

38:27.924 --> 38:29.957
We save lives.

38:30.609 --> 38:33.556
- We deserve to be paid for it.
- Amen.

38:39.825 --> 38:41.658
Great to see you back.

38:41.668 --> 38:43.869
It's good to be seen, Dr. Hawkins.

38:43.879 --> 38:46.877
Don't know what you said to
convince them to rehire

38:46.887 --> 38:50.940
some old ER nurse, but thanks.
I owe you a beer.

38:50.950 --> 38:53.503
- I'd say it's the other way around.
- [LAUGHS]

38:53.514 --> 38:57.100
- This place is a wreck without you.
- I heard today was a rough one.

38:57.111 --> 38:59.643
It's a good thing you were here
to take over.

38:59.653 --> 39:01.709
Which reminds me...

39:01.720 --> 39:03.927
a janitor turned this in.

39:03.936 --> 39:05.551
He found it on the floor.

39:05.560 --> 39:07.805
Might belong to your John Doe.

39:14.639 --> 39:15.811
"Mom: How's Atlanta? Hot?"
"Mom: Erik did you get there ok?"

39:15.812 --> 39:17.041
"Mom: Call me right away. I mean it."
"Mom: I'm really worried. Please call"

39:18.810 --> 39:20.730
Thank you.

39:20.740 --> 39:22.614
You're welcome.

39:37.492 --> 39:39.526
[SIGHS]

39:40.776 --> 39:43.067
[LINE RINGING]

39:46.300 --> 39:47.948
Hello?

39:47.958 --> 39:51.424
This is Dr. Conrad Hawkins
at Chastain Park Memorial.

39:51.434 --> 39:53.446
Is this Erik's mom?

39:56.304 --> 39:58.638
I have some bad news.

39:59.983 --> 40:04.267
Your son came into our ER today
after an accident.

40:05.090 --> 40:08.951
[FADING]: He had a head injury
that was very serious.

40:08.960 --> 40:11.449
We did everything possible,

40:11.460 --> 40:15.349
but unfortunately, we couldn't save him.

40:18.443 --> 40:21.043
[DEVON SIGHS]

40:24.040 --> 40:27.402
What do you say we get away
together for a few days? Just us.

40:27.412 --> 40:30.359
That sounds nice.
Where are you thinking?

40:30.368 --> 40:31.786
I don't know.

40:31.795 --> 40:33.507
Kitty Hawk.

40:33.516 --> 40:37.470
If we're gonna take time off work,
we have to go someplace good.

40:37.479 --> 40:40.010
All right. Wherever you want to go.

40:40.019 --> 40:42.881
As long as I'm with you.

40:42.890 --> 40:44.350
Kauai.

40:44.360 --> 40:46.718
Just tell me when.

40:51.765 --> 40:54.319
[GROANS SOFTLY]

40:55.500 --> 40:56.693
Oh, don't leave. Come back here.

40:56.700 --> 41:00.179
[LAUGHS] Let me get my computer.
I need to work.

41:00.189 --> 41:02.514
So what are you working on?

41:02.524 --> 41:05.326
This is my own thing.

41:05.337 --> 41:09.187
A group of people not far from
here got some rare sickness.

41:09.197 --> 41:12.326
They think it has something
to do with the drinking water.

41:12.336 --> 41:15.794
Who knows. Could be the
next Flint, Michigan.

41:15.804 --> 41:19.218
If it is, I'm going to find the story.

41:21.161 --> 41:22.950
I'm proud of you.

41:26.230 --> 41:27.828
Proud of you.

41:27.840 --> 41:30.343
♪ ♪

41:30.353 --> 41:32.500
[DEVON SIGHS]

41:32.510 --> 41:35.500
♪ And I've walked a dark ♪
♪ and narrow road... ♪

41:35.510 --> 41:37.835
[LAUGHING]: I'm so glad you called.

41:37.845 --> 41:39.897
Well, it's just so nice
to get out for a beer.

41:39.907 --> 41:42.548
And great that you don't have to
work late or do a double.

41:42.558 --> 41:46.017
The hours at the clinic are great.
I get to help my kid with homework.

41:46.027 --> 41:50.343
I was gonna ask you, um,
what it's like to work for Dr. Hunter.

41:51.788 --> 41:55.739
We just had massive budget cuts
at Chastain, so you know,

41:55.749 --> 41:58.760
just checking to see if there's
any greener grass.

41:58.770 --> 42:00.587
I heard. That sucks.

42:00.597 --> 42:02.854
Um, I like working for Hunter.

42:02.865 --> 42:05.149
I mean, the pay is good,
so are the benefits.

42:05.159 --> 42:08.777
She doesn't freak out if I have to
take the day off 'cause my kid's sick.

42:08.787 --> 42:12.311
- And it looks like a health spa.
- The patients love it.

42:12.321 --> 42:15.859
Well, as much as they can.
Cancer's brutal.

42:17.790 --> 42:20.690
You know, I noticed working with
her patients at Chastain...

42:20.700 --> 42:25.098
The chemo dosages she
uses are really high.

42:26.854 --> 42:31.959
I'm not a doctor, but I know she
puts a lot of thought into coming up

42:31.969 --> 42:35.490
with the protocol for each patient.
Everyone is unique.

42:35.500 --> 42:38.267
That's terrific.

42:38.277 --> 42:40.336
Yeah.

42:40.736 --> 42:43.140
If you do decide you want
to work for Dr. Hunter,

42:43.150 --> 42:45.118
one thing I can tell you is,

42:45.128 --> 42:48.069
she likes everyone who works
for her to be discreet.

42:48.079 --> 42:50.004
Maybe that's why it was so difficult

42:50.014 --> 42:52.799
to get a patient file from your office.

42:58.163 --> 43:01.946
I just remembered that my sitter
has to leave early tonight, so...

43:01.955 --> 43:04.790
Oh, well, maybe another time.

43:04.800 --> 43:06.521
Sure.

43:06.530 --> 43:08.490
♪ Can see our scars ♪

43:08.500 --> 43:11.260
♪ It's what we're made of ♪

43:11.270 --> 43:31.654
♪ It's who we are. ♪

43:51.050 --> 43:53.010
Captioned by
Media Access Group at WGBH

43:55.250 --> 43:57.380
You've survived your shift
with The Resident.

43:57.420 --> 43:59.690
Now here are a few more shows
to check out from Fox.

44:02.260 --> 44:03.830
It's time we fly
this old bird.

44:03.860 --> 44:06.790
♪ It feels good ♪

44:06.830 --> 44:09.700
MULDER: I want to believe.
I would just like to see.

44:09.730 --> 44:10.500
I can help you.

44:10.530 --> 44:12.500
♪ It feels good ♪

44:12.530 --> 44:14.140
-You want to do the honours, Alan?
-Yeah!

44:14.170 --> 44:15.500
No, you never
touch this.

44:15.540 --> 44:17.300
♪ You know it feels good ♪

44:17.340 --> 44:18.910
-♪ It feels good ♪

44:18.940 --> 44:20.880
♪ Oh, you know it feels good ♪

44:20.910 --> 44:22.980
Let's do it.

44:23.010 --> 44:25.280
Everything you thought
you knew about medicine is wrong.

44:28.420 --> 44:29.350
Unbelievable.

44:29.380 --> 44:30.950
♪ It feels good ♪

